  "local_port": 37688,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What books could I use to teach myself math from the ground up?",
  "response": "If you're looking to teach yourself math from the ground up, you'll want to start with basic arithmetic and gradually progress to more advanced topics. Here\u2019s a list of books that can guide you through this process, covering a wide range of mathematical topics:\n\n### Basic Arithmetic and Pre-Algebra\n1. **\"Arithmetic and Algebra... again?\" by Marek Pawlikowski and Jeanine Meyer**\n   - This book is designed for adults who want to refresh or learn basic arithmetic and algebra. It covers the fundamentals in a clear and approachable manner.\n\n2. **\"Prealgebra\" by Richard Rusczyk**\n   - Published by the Art of Problem Solving, this book is excellent for self-learners. It covers pre-algebra concepts with plenty of examples and exercises.\n\n### Algebra\n3. **\"Algebra\" by Michael Artin**\n   - This is a comprehensive introduction to algebra that starts with the basics and builds up to more advanced topics. Artin\u2019s approach is rigorous but accessible.\n\n4. **\"Introduction to Algebra\" by Richard Rusczyk**\n   - Another Art of Problem Solving book, this one is great for learning algebra through problem-solving. It includes detailed explanations and numerous problems.\n\n### Geometry\n5. **\"Euclidean Geometry: A Comprehensive Introduction\" by Robin Hartshorne**\n   - This book provides a thorough introduction to Euclidean geometry, suitable for self-study. It covers both the basics and more advanced concepts.\n\n6. **\"Geometry: Seeing, Doing, Understanding\" by Harold R. Jacobs**\n   - This book is known for its clear explanations and engaging approach, making it suitable for self-learners. It includes many hands-on activities.\n\n### Trigonometry\n7. **\"Trigonometry\" by Charles P. McKeague and Mark D. Turner**\n   - A straightforward and thorough textbook on trigonometry. It includes plenty of examples and exercises to help you understand the concepts.\n\n### Calculus\n8. **\"Calculus\" by Michael Spivak**\n   - This is a classic calculus textbook that is both rigorous and accessible. It\u2019s perfect for self-study and covers both single and multivariable calculus.\n\n9. **\"Calculus: Early Transcendentals\" by James Stewart**\n   - This book is widely used and covers calculus in depth. It includes many examples and exercises, making it suitable for self-learners.\n\n### Linear Algebra\n10. **\"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler**\n    - This book provides a clear and comprehensive introduction to linear algebra. It\u2019s designed to be used by students learning on their own.\n\n11. **\"Introduction to Linear Algebra\" by Gilbert Strang**\n    - Another excellent book on linear algebra, known for its clear explanations and practical approach. It\u2019s highly recommended for self-study.\n\n### Statistics and Probability\n12. **\"Statistics in Plain English\" by Timothy C. Urdan**\n    - This book provides an easy-to-understand introduction to statistics. It\u2019s perfect for beginners and those looking to self-study.\n\n13. **\"A First Course in Probability\" by Sheldon Ross**\n    - A thorough and accessible introduction to probability theory. It includes many examples and exercises to help you grasp the concepts.\n\n### Advanced Topics\n14. **\"Abstract Algebra\" by David S. Dummit and Richard M. Foote**\n    - This is a comprehensive textbook on abstract algebra, suitable for those looking to delve deeper into the subject.\n\n15. **\"Real and Complex Analysis\" by Walter Rudin**\n    - A classic in the field, this book covers real and complex analysis at an advanced level. It\u2019s challenging but rewarding for self-learners.\n\nThese books should provide a solid foundation and guide you through the various levels of mathematics. Remember to work through the exercises in each book, as practice is essential for mastering math.",
